  "prompt": "Why am I allergic to dogs and not to cats?",
  "response": "Allergies to dogs and cats are caused by different proteins found in their dander, saliva, and urine. The specific reasons why you might be allergic to dogs but not cats can vary, but here are some possible explanations:\n\n1. Different allergen proteins: Dogs and cats produce different proteins that can trigger allergic reactions. The primary dog allergen (Can f 1) is different from the primary cat allergen (Fel d 1).\n\n2. Protein structure: The molecular structure of these allergens differs, which can affect how your immune system responds to them.\n\n3. Individual immune system sensitivity: Your immune system may be more reactive to dog allergens than cat allergens.\n\n4. Exposure and genetics: Your genetic predisposition and previous exposure to these animals can influence your allergic response.\n\n5. Breed differences: Some dog breeds produce fewer allergens than others, which can affect allergic reactions.\n\nIt's important to note that allergy sensitivity can change over time, and what you're allergic to now might differ from what you were allergic to in the past. If you're concerned about your allergies, consulting an allergist can provide more personalized insights.",
